Cervantes says in Don Quixote that a hand being hairy and sinewy is a sign of the great strength of its owner. In Russian criminal slang a "hairy hand" ("–≤–æ–ª–æ—Å–∞—Ç–∞—è —Ä—É–∫–∞", "–º–æ—Ö–Ω–∞—Ç–∞—è –ª–∞–ø–∞") is a way to refer to connections in high places, like knowing an ex-KGB mafia boss type.

An interesting parallel between Spanish and Russian culture. It reminds me of how Fr. Stephen de Young talked about on Lord of Spirits of how Nephilim being called "mighty men of old" has the same connotation as calling dictators a "strongman", political and physical strength.

Physiologically I guess hairiness of the hand might mean less fine innervation which will mean no fine motor control but increased brute strength like in apes. So I guess it symbolizes a type of physiology that is brutish and crude but very strong and insensitive. It's intuitive.
